    <div class="section firstReview">
      

<div id="review_709001074" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/709001074" />
    <a title="VaultOfBooks" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3929792-vaultofbooks"><img alt="VaultOfBooks" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1348989948p2/3929792.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/709001074?book_show_action=true">Sep 01, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="VaultOfBooks" class="user" itemprop="url" name="VaultOfBooks" href="/user/show/3929792-vaultofbooks">VaultOfBooks</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer709001074" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10696087439027243142">By Meghna Pant. Grade: A+<br/><br/>Meghna Pant is an Indian author and financial journalist. She has written one novel, One &amp; A Half Wife, and a collection of short stories, Happy Birthday! Pant’s short stories have been published in over a dozen literary magazines, including Avatar Review, Wasafari, Eclectica, and QLRS.<br/><br/>“The Gola Master” is about a man who is helpless and woeful, being injured and hurt from his failed marriage, has a son who is no longer his, and a past that he is too ashamed to admit bec</span>
  <span id="freeText10696087439027243142" style="display:none">By Meghna Pant. Grade: A+<br /><br />Meghna Pant is an Indian author and financial journalist. She has written one novel, One &amp; A Half Wife, and a collection of short stories, Happy Birthday! Pant’s short stories have been published in over a dozen literary magazines, including Avatar Review, Wasafari, Eclectica, and QLRS.<br /><br />“The Gola Master” is about a man who is helpless and woeful, being injured and hurt from his failed marriage, has a son who is no longer his, and a past that he is too ashamed to admit because of the “class of society” that he is a part of now.<br /><br />“Hoopsters” is about a girl who is pessimistic about everything in life and believes that all poor people are either thieves or killers.<br /><br />“Happy Birthday” is about a woman called Nadia who is the perfect Indian wife and despite her lifeless marriage and her husband’s infidelity, remains loyal to her hurting bondage. A flashback of her last novel.<br /><br />“Friends” explores the selfless relevancy that is friendship.<br /><br />“Lemon and Chilli” describes a man’s pain and sadness which is caused from his own actions, how he deals with it and how it affects his decisions regarding family.<br /><br />“Clips and Cane” explores the mindset of a poor, blind chair maker while he deals with a sad past, heartbreak and betrayal.<br /><br />“Shaitans” portrays how destiny works hand in hand with karma.<br /><br />Each story is more overwhelming than the last. Each end leaves the reader astounded and amazed, at the same time feeling sympathetic towards the characters of the story. Each story has an unpredictable turn, a heart rending back story and a soul stirring plot.<br /><br />(Quote)<br />“I try not to look outside but when our car passes him, Kaka’s smile, which contains the last fragment of my childhood, fades. I turn away.”<br />(Quote Ends)<br /><br />The narrative is agonizing and knife-sharp.<br /><br />(Quote)<br />“I took four hundred dollars – equivalent to the loan Baba had taken – and burned the notes. I put the remains in a copper urn and dispersed them in the Hudson; the ashes of family, of strife, and of tallying up your life’s score and realizing that you came to naught.”<br />(quote ends)<br /><br />This book will make even the toughest of hearts melt and cry. There will be instances in the book where the reader would be forced to accept the truth about society and its functioning, and uncomfortable truths we ignore about ourselves.<br /><br />(Quote)<br />“Though her sari was as bright as the chandeliers in the high ceiling, the women around her were flaunting their assets to greater effect: the lower the neckline and the shorter the dress, the richer they were.”<br />(Quote Ends)<br /><br />Filled with heavy-hearted, deplorable and sympathetic characters, this is a recommended read for all.<br /><br /><br />Originally reviewed at Vaultofbooks.com, a close-knit community of fanatical readers. We are looking for perceptive readers who can write well, and we are eager to provide lots of free books in exchange for reviews. Shoot us a mail at contact@vaultofbooks.com</span>
  <a data-text-id="10696087439027243142" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


